[49m[38;5;9m- 1230      [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Patient-facing documentation.** Patients may receive transcripts as part of HIPAA right-of-access requests. The patient-facing experience of the transcript (formatting, redaction of bystander content where appropriate, behavioral-health-specific handling) is a workflow design problem. Document the institutional policy on transcript disclosure, train the medical-records team on the policy, and update patient-facing privacy notices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-facing documentation.** Patients may receive transcripts as part of HIPAA right-of-access requests. The patient-facing experience of the transcript (formatting, redaction of bystander content where appropriate, behavioral-health-specific handling) is a workflow design problem. Document the institutional policy on transcript disclosure, train the medical-records team on the policy, and update patient-facing privacy notices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Versioned deployment pattern with canary inference and rollback.** Every artifact that influences pipeline output (ASR model, custom-vocabulary version, custom-language-model version, diarization model, note-generation model_id, faithfulness-judge model_id, contradiction-rule catalog version, per-specialty template version, per-language asset versions) is versioned in source control with commit-SHA-tied builds. Production deployments use a canary inference profile with traffic-shift (5% canary, automatic promotion after the held-out evaluation set passes the regression gate). The held-out evaluation set includes per-language samples, per-specialty samples, per-audio-quality-band samples, faithfulness-edge-case samples, structured-extraction-edge-case samples, and prompt-injection test cases. Rollback-on-regression is triggered when the canary's faithfulness score, per-cohort WER, or structured-extraction acceptance rate drops below the held-out set's regression threshold. Every encounter audit record is version-stamped with all artifact versions (ASR model, custom vocabulary, custom language model, diarization model, note-generation model_id, faithfulness-judge model_id, contradiction-rule catalog version, per-specialty template version, per-language asset versions) so that production incidents can be traced to specific artifact versions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Lambda resource-based policies and event-payload validation.** Each Lambda's resource-based policy pins the invoking principal to the production-stage ARN of its expected caller: the production API Gateway stage ARN (for clinician-facing Lambdas), the production Step Functions state-machine ARN (for pipeline-stage Lambdas), or the production EventBridge rule ARN (for event-driven Lambdas). As a defense-in-depth layer, each Lambda includes an event-payload validation guard at function entry that verifies the invoking context (requestContext.apiId for API Gateway callers, the state-machine ARN in the execution context for Step Functions callers, the EventBridge source for event-driven callers) against production constants. Invocations from unexpected principals or with unexpected context are rejected and logged as security events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-visit-type audio retention with configurable windows.** Audio retention is not a single institutional setting. It varies by visit type and regulatory profile: primary care visits retain audio for 7-30 days (the clinical-quality review window); behavioral-health visits retain audio for 24-72 hours (shorter due to sensitivity); 42-CFR-Part-2-eligible visits retain audio for 24-48 hours (minimal retention consistent with QA needs). Each retention window is enforced through S3 lifecycle policies on per-visit-type key prefixes. The privacy officer reviews and approves the per-visit-type retention configuration before launch and annually thereafter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Retention floor: longest-of rule.** Audit-log and transcript retention is sized to the longest of: HIPAA six-year minimum; state-specific medical-records-retention rules (including pediatric-records-extending-to-age-of-majority-plus-X in applicable jurisdictions); EHR vendor audit-retention floor; telehealth-platform vendor audit-retention floor; 42 CFR Part 2 disclosure-accounting log retention for Part-2-eligible visits; and the institutional regulatory floor. The compliance team documents the binding floor per data class and reviews it when jurisdiction or vendor relationships change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **42 CFR Part 2 and state-level confidentiality compliance.** Behavioral-health visits where substance-use treatment is discussed or where the patient is enrolled in a substance-use-treatment program may be subject to 42 CFR Part 2, which imposes consent and disclosure requirements stricter than baseline HIPAA. The architecture supports a behavioral-health profile as an explicit configuration: (a) retention: 24-48 hours for Part-2-eligible audio, enforced by dedicated S3 lifecycle rules on a Part-2-eligible prefix; (b) access control: separate KMS key class with tighter key policy limited to the treating clinician, an assigned clinical-quality reviewer with explicit Part-2 access, and the privacy officer; (c) consent flow: behavioral-health-specific disclosure plus explicit Part-2 disclosure-and-consent at intake for substance-use-treatment-eligible visits; (d) patient-portal release: gated on additional clinician review and caregiver-proxy compatibility check; (e) audit-log discipline: separate audit-archive prefix with disclosure-accounting metadata; (f) cross-encounter analytics: excluded by default; inclusion requires explicit institutional review. The visit-state record at Step 1C captures behavioral_health_profile and part_2_eligible flags. The audit record at Step 7 includes the profile flags and the applied retention/access-control class. The privacy officer is the canonical owner of the Part-2 configuration and the rule catalogs that define which visits are Part-2-eligible.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort asset maintenance.** Per-cohort accuracy and adoption monitoring is a launch gate and an ongoing operational discipline, not a post-launch dashboard. The cohort axes are: single-axis cohorts (per-language, per-specialty, per-clinician, per-audio-quality-band, per-patient-age-band, per-visit-type) and two-axis cohorts (per-language-by-audio-quality, per-specialty-by-language). Each cohort has a minimum sample size for statistical reliability. Per-cohort threshold metrics include per-channel WER, diarization error rate, per-layer faithfulness score, structured-extraction acceptance rate, edit distance, and sustained-adoption rate at 30/90/180 days. The launch gate requires every defined cohort to meet its threshold; the institution-wide average is informational only. Per-cohort drift detection and alerting trigger review when a cohort's metrics drift below threshold. Audio-quality-band is a per-encounter feature that drives lower confidence thresholds for poor-audio encounters and surfaces an audio-quality warning in the clinician's review interface for those visits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster recovery topology.** Each pipeline stage has an explicit failover policy: Transcribe regional outage triggers cross-region fallback (if the institution has pre-configured a secondary region) or degraded-mode-record-only-no-transcript with post-outage batch reprocessing; Bedrock unavailability triggers template-only note generation falling back to manual documentation; Comprehend Medical unavailability triggers LLM-only structured-extraction; EHR API unreachable triggers durable note storage in the speech-to-text system until EHR confirmation (retry with exponential backoff); telehealth-platform unavailable means the visit does not occur and the speech-to-text feature is disabled. Failover-detection triggers are CloudWatch alarms on per-service error-rate thresholds. Failover-back triggers are CloudWatch OK-state transitions sustained for the configured recovery-confirmation window. Quarterly DR testing validates each failover path end-to-end and documents the failover and failover-back durations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Retrieved-context content supply-chain integrity.** The note-generation prompt retrieves patient history from the EHR as context. If the EHR's patient-history content has been corrupted or tampered with, the LLM's generated note inherits the corruption. The defense is: validate the retrieved patient context against the EHR's audit trail (confirm the content was authored by a credentialed clinician and has not been modified outside normal clinical workflows); treat the patient-history channel as untrusted input (delimited framing in the prompt, faithfulness check as a downstream guard); and log the patient-history retrieval source and version for each note generation so that corrupted-context incidents can be traced.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+       1248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-language pipeline asset requirements.** Each supported language requires its own full set of pipeline assets before launch: per-language ASR configuration with custom vocabulary and custom language model; per-language note-generation prompt with native-speaker clinical-informatics input; per-language template definitions; per-language faithfulness rule catalogs; per-language diarization tuning; per-language structured-extraction approach (where Comprehend Medical does not directly support the language, fall back to translation-then-extract or LLM-driven extraction with per-language prompts). Build for day one even when shipping English-first: the per-language asset structure, the per-language deployment gate, and the per-language sample-size minimums are architectural choices, not post-launch additions. Each per-language deployment is gated on the per-language assets meeting the institutional thresholds and per-language minimum sample sizes for statistical reliability.
