[49m[38;5;9m- 155     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Faithfulness as a hard constraint.** The same faithfulness concern from recipe 10.4 (and from the broader LLM recipes in chapter 2) applies here, sharply. The LLM must not invent clinical content that was not in the transcript. The summary is a faithful structuring of what was actually said, not a rewriting that fills in plausible-sounding details. Faithfulness checks (does every claim in the summary have a transcript citation; is the cited transcript segment actually supportive of the claim) run as a defense layer before the summary is shown to the clinician. 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Faithfulness as a hard constraint.** The same faithfulness concern from recipe 10.4 (and from the broader LLM recipes in chapter 2) applies here, sharply. The LLM must not invent clinical content that was not in the transcript. The summary is a faithful structuring of what was actually said, not a rewriting that fills in plausible-sounding details. Faithfulness is enforced through a layered architecture rather than a single defense:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Layer 1 (cheap, synchronous, every note):** Citation grounding verification (every claim in the generated note must have a transcript segment reference) and structured-output schema validation (the generated JSON conforms to the expected schema with no unexpected fields). This layer is fast and catches the most common failures. Disposition: block the note from being shown to the clinician if citation grounding fails.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Layer 2 (parallel, synchronous, every note):** LLM-judge faithfulness scoring (a separate, often smaller model scores each claim against its cited transcript segment for semantic fidelity) and clinical-rule-based contradiction detection (hard-coded rules catch the known-dangerous patterns: "denies X" vs. "reports X," medication-name substitutions, temporal-modifier changes). Disposition: flag for clinician attention if the faithfulness score is below threshold; block if contradictions are detected. For the behavioral-health profile, disposition thresholds are tighter (lower flagging threshold, lower blocking threshold).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Layer 3 (offline, sampled, feeds improvement):** Clinical-quality team reviews a sample of generated notes against transcripts on a defined cadence (weekly for the first three months, monthly thereafter). Findings feed back into Layer 1 rule updates and Layer 2 prompt tuning. This layer detects failure patterns that the automated checks miss.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Per-layer disposition (block vs. flag) is policy-driven and configured per visit-type profile. Per-cohort faithfulness-failure rate is both a launch gate and an ongoing operational gate. The clinical-quality officer owns the rule catalogs (Layer 2 contradiction rules). The clinical-informatics lead owns the grounding rules (Layer 1 citation validation logic). Both roles are named at system launch.
